MEM HUB PUNCTURES DRUM WITH FORKLIFT, 1 OF 4 PER WOODEN PALLET, DURING LOADING INTO TRAILER.  MEM HUB THEN SENDS TRAILER, WITH LEAKING, DAMAGED DRUM TO LOCAL HEAVYWEIGHT STATION ('OLVRT'), APPROXIMATELY 5 MILES FROM MEM HUB.  LEAKING DRUM IS DISCOVERED DURING OFFLOAD OF TRAILER, WHICH CONTAINS APPROX 13 PALLETS OF DRUMS, ALL CONTAINING SAME MATERIAL.  THE MATERIAL DOES NOT READILY EVAPORATE NOR PRODUCE ODORS, SO THE LEAK IS NOT DETECTED UNTIL ACTUALLY OBSERVED, EARLY ON 8/3.  THE DAMAGED DRUM IS PLACED IN A STEEL SALVAGE DRUM, AND SENT ON TO DESTINATION.  IN ADDITION TO MEM HUB TRANSPORTING DAMAGED DRUM IN VIOLATION OF COMPANY POLICY, OLVRT STATION DOES NOT REPORT THE SPILL UNTIL 8/5/96, DUE TO COMPLAINTS FROM EMPLOYEES OF MISC ITCHING AND BURNING SENSATIONS OF EYES AND NOSE.  EIGHT OLVRT EMPLOYEES GO TO LOCAL HOSPITAL, BUT ARE RELEASED AFTER SHORT OBSERVATION, NONE ARE ADMITTED TO THE HOSPITAL, AND ALL EIGHT EMPLOYEES RETURN TO WORK THE NEXT DAY.  CORPORATE SAFETY IS CONTINUING INVESTIGATION, AND FOLLOWUP AND CORRECTIVE ACTION IS UNDERWAY WITH BOTH MEM HUB AND OLVRT TO PREVENT ANY FUTURE OCCURRENCE.
VEHICULAR ACCIDENT.

A TOTALLY DESTROYED AMERSHAM PACKAGE WAS DISCOVERED ON THE RAMP/DRIVE AREA AT THE FEDEX INDIANAPOLIS HUB OPERATION.  THE ONLY ITEM FOUND WAS THE SHREDDED 7A TYPE A FIBERBOARD BOX.  IT IS BELIEVED A RAMP TUG OR CONTAINER DOLLY RAN OVER THIS PACKAGE.  THE INNER CONTENTS (721 MICRO-CURIES OF P-32 [LIQUID FORM] CONTAINED WITHIN A PLASTIC PIG) WERE NOT RECOVERED.  HUB DANGEROUS GOODS REACT TEAM CONDUCTED NUMEROUS EXTENSIVE SEARCHES EXTENDING OVER THE ENTIRE WEEKEND WITHOUT LOCATING THE PIG.  ALL GARBAGE UNITS, DUMPSTERS, STORM DRAINS, AND FOD SWEEPERS WERE CHECKED WITH NO POSITIVE RESULTS.  THE NRC WAS NOTIFIED BY FEDEX'S RADIATION PHYSICIST, DR. ROY PARKER.  THE LOCAL FAA OFFICE WAS ALSO NOTIFIED OF THE INCIDENT.  THE INDIANA DEPARTMENT OF HEALTH & SAFETY DISPATCHED TWO SPECIALISTS WITH MONITORING EQUIPMENT TO CHECK FOR THE SOURCE AND POSSIBLE SURFACE CONTAMINATION.  THEY FOUND NEITHER.  AT THE PRINTING OF THIS REPORT, THE SOURCE IS STILL MISSING.  THE EXPERTS BELIEVE THE SOURCE IS NO LONGER AROUND THE HUB AREA.  ACCORDING TO DR. PARKER, DUE TO THE RELATIVE LOW ACTIVITY OF THE MATERIAL AND IT'S SHORT HALF-LIFE, THE HAZARD TO HUMANS AND ANIMALS IS PRESENTLY NEGLIGIBLE.

column168: OUR SEMI-TANKER WAS SOUTH BOUND ON I-94 IN MILWAUKEE WHEN ANOTHER SEMI-VAN WAS ENTERING I-94 SOUTH BOUND AT THE LAYTON AVE ENTRANCE RAMP.  THE SEMI-VAN WAS ENTERNG AT AN EXCESSIVE SPEED ON A CURVED RAMP WHEN HIS LOAD SHIFTED TO THE LEFT AND HIS TRACTOR AND TRAILER TIPPED OVER ON ITS SIDE AS IT ENTERED I-94.  THE CORNER OF HIS TRAILER RIPPED A LONG GASH IN OUR TANK TRAILER CAUSING A RELEASE OF GASOLINE AND A FIRE.  THE FIRE WAS EXTINGUISHED BY THE MILWAUKEE FIRE DEPT.  4100 GALS OF GASOLINE WAS SALVAGED FROM THE FRONT COMPARTMENTS OF THE SEMI-TANKER OF THE 3900 GALS THAT WAS IN THE BACK COMPARTMENTS.  ABOUT 3000 GALS SPILLED AND OR BURNED EITHER ON THE PAVEMENT, IN THE STORM SEWER, OR IN THE DAMAGED REAR OF THE TANKER.  NATIONAL TANK SERVICE OF WI (SEE ATTACHED HAZ MAT SHIPPING PAPER) RECOVERED ABOUT 1300 GALS OF SLOP FROM THE DAMAGED REAR OF THE TRAILER. OF THAT 1300 GALS ABOUT 900 GALS WAS GASOLINE AND 400 GALS WAS CHEMICALS AND FOAM USED TO EXTINGUISH THE FIRE.  SUPERIOR SPECIAL SERVICES OF FOND-DU-LAC, WI CLEANED UP THE RESIDUE IN THE STORM SEWER WITH THE DIRECTION OF THE WI DNR.

THE ABOVE MENTIONED BOOKING ARRIVED AT OUR FACILITY AT APPROXIMATELY 8:00 AM THIS MORNING AND WAS DEVANNED. AFTER UNLOADING OF THE CONTAINER, WE DISCOVERED THAT TWO (2) CARTONS EACH SAID TO CONTAIN 5 GALLONS OF ORGANIC PEROXIDE HAD BEEN PUNCTURED AND WERE EMPTY. THERE WAS NO VISIBLE EVIDENCE OF ANY REMAINING PRODUCT. THE CARTONS AROUND THE PUNCTURED CONTAINERS WERE DRY AND UNSTAINED. THERE WAS NO DAMPNESS OR STAIN ON THE PALLET CONTAINING THE PRODUCT. ON INSPECTION OF THE FLOOR OF THE CONTAINER WHERE THE PALLET WAS PLACED THERE WAS NO PRESENCE OF DAMPNESS OR STAIN TO INDICATE THE PRESENCE OF A SPILL. THE EMPTY CONTAINERS THEMSELVES WERE DRY AND DISPOSED OF ACCORDINGLY. ** THE SHIPMENT CONTAINED A TOTAL OF 5 PALLETS AND DURING THE UNLOADING PROCESS OUR WAREHOUSE NOTED THAT THE PALLETS WERE OVER LAPPED IN STOW. IN RETROSPECT, THIS OVERLAPPING MAY HAVE CAUSED THE CONTAINER PUNCTURES SINCE THE 2 EMPTY AND DAMAGED CARTONS WERE LOCATED ON THE BOTTOM ROW OF THE PALLET WITH THE ADJACENT PALLET RESTING ON TOP OF IT'S CORNER. ** AS YOU ARE AWARE, OUR NORMAL PROCEDURE IS TO TAKE PICTURES OF ANY AND ALL DAMAGED CARGO WHILE IT IS STILL PRESENT IN THE CONTAINER. SINCE THERE WAS NO APPARENT DAMAGE DURING INITIAL UNLOADING OF THE CARGO, NO PICTURES WERE TAKEN. THE ACTUAL DAMAGE TO THE CARTONS WAS NOT DISCOVERED UNTIL THE PRODUCT WAS PLACED IN OUR HAZARDOUS MATERIAL AREA FOR STORAGE UNTIL LOADING TO FINAL DESTINATION. ** IF YOU HAVE ANY QUESTIONS, PLEASE ADVISE ACCORDINGLY.

column168: WEARING PROPER PPE RESPONDED TO DOOR 8 ABSORBED A LIQUID USING THE DECISION TREE AND FLAMMABLE LIQUID RESPONSE SHEET. DMP DECONTAIMINATED PPE.

PACKAGE WAS DISCOVERED LEAKING IN DOOR 9 TRAILER #620142 AT 3:30 BY SAM HARTFIELD.  HAZARDOUS RESPONDE WAS CALLED, USING DECISION TREE AND PROPER PPE, FOLLOWED THE FLAMMABLE LIQUID RESPONSE SHEET, HE CLEANED UP SPILL WITH CLAY BASED ABSORBANT AND REMOVED THE PACKAGE TO DAMAGE PACKAGE CENTER.  THE TOTAL CONTENTS WERE DISPOSED OF THROUGH DMP.
NO REMARKS

DRIVER ARRIVED TO UNLOAD, AND WHILE WAITING FOR OPERATOR, HOOKED UP TO WHAT HE THOUGHT TO BE UNLOADING LINE.  (NOT CLEARLY MARKED).  ON ARRIVAL OF OPERATOR, WHO ADVISED TO START UNLOADING WHENEVER HE WAS READY .  LINE HOOKED TO WAS A SEPERATE LINE USED FOR RELIEVING PRESSURE ON TANK WHEN UNLOADING COMPLETED, WHICH TERMINATED OUT OF VIEW OF DRIVER.  SPILL WAS CONTAINED, NEUTRALIZED AND CLEANED UP BY CTL EMPLOYEE AND SWS EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR PERSONNEL.

AT APPROXIMATELY 3:00 AM LEADMAN, LARRY MCCALL, DISCOVERED A CHEMICAL SPILL ON INBOUND UNIT TRAILER 53079 FROM ATLANTA GA.  THE CHEMICAL HAD SPILLED FROM TOP OF TOTE TANK IN TRANSIT.  THE SPILL WAS CONTAINED TO TRAILER, ADVISED DOCKMAN TO BACK OFF UNTIL OI ARRIVED AT 4:00AM.  LOOSED AT SPILL, GOT PAPER WORK AND LOOKED UP IN EMERGENCY RESPONSE GUIDEBOOK. CALLED CHEMTREC AT APPROXIMATELY 4:10AM, THEY CONTACTED SHIPPER AND HE CALLED AT APPROXIMATELY 4:20 AM.  DESCRIBED THE ACCIDENT TO HIM.  THE BUNG ON TOP OF TOTE HAD WORKED ITS WAY LOOSE LETTING THE CONTENTS SPLASH FROM CONTAINER ON TO TOP OF TOTE AND WALL OF TRAILER RUNNING ONTO THE FLOOR OF TRAILER.  VOLUME WASTED APPROXIMATELY 10 GALLON MR. HINTON WITH SHIPPER ASKED ME COULD WE DO CLEAN UP, I STATED IT DEPENDS ON WHAT THIS IS AND WHAT HE ADVISED WAS TOLD ITS PG111 LOW TOXIC WITH NO INHALATION HAZARD. IF COMES IN CONTACT WITH MATERIAL WASH WITH SOAP AND WATER, WASH CLOTHING BEFORE REUSE, WITH THIS INFORMATION WE DID THE CLEAN UP.

DRIVER LOSE CONTROL MAKING A RIGHT TURN AT INTERSECTION OF NARROWS AND NEW CASTLE ROADS.  THERE WAS NO RELEASE OF PRODUCT WHEN OVERTURNED.  TRAILER WAS UPRIGHTED WITH NO FURTHER INCIDENT AND PRODUCT WAS OFF LOADED WITH NO SPILL OR LEAK.  APPROXIMATELY 10-15 PEOPLE IN THE IMMEIDATE AREA WERE EVACUATED DURING THE UPRIGHTING AND UNLOADING PROCESS.

A VAN TRAILER CONTAINING HAZARDOUS WASTE WAS ENROUTE FROM AMOCO CHEMICAL COMPANY LOCATED 2 MILES SOUTH OF FM 2004 & FM29178 IN ALVIN, TX TO CLEAN HARBORS OF BRAINTREE, INC.  LOCATED AT 385 QUINCY AVENUE IN BRAINTREE, MA. DURING A ROUTINE STOP AT SPRING GROVE AVENUE IN CINCINNATI, OH IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT APROXIMATELY 1 PINT OF MATERIAL HAD ESCAPED FROM THE TOP CLOSURE OF 1 OF THE CONTAINER ONTO THE FLOOR OF THE CAN TRAILER AND THE ASPHALT PARKING AREA.  FACILITY PERSONNNEL IMMEDIATELY CONTAINED THE RELEASE AND ABSORBED ALL FREE LIQUID WITH SPEEDI DRY.  ALL CLEAN-UP DEBRIS GENERATED AS A RESULT OF THE RELEASE WAS PLACED INTO A SUITABLE CONTAINER AND WAS PLACED INTO STORAGE PENDING OFF-SITE DISPOSAL.  AN INSPECTION OF THE LEAKING CLOSURE ON THE DRUMS.  PRIOR TO CONTINUNG TRANSPORTATION, THE CLOSURE DEVICE WAS TIGHTENED AND ALL REMAINING DRUMS WERE INSPECTED TO INSURE THE CLOSURES WERE SECURE.  PRIOR TO DEPARTURE FROM THE SHIPPER'S LOCATION, ALL CONTAINERS WERE INSPECTED AND NO EVIDENCE OF LEAKING WAS OBSERVED.  DRIVERS WILL CONTINUE TO INSPECT EACH CONTAINER AS IT IS LOADED AND WILL CONTINUE TO TAKE APPROPRIATE ACTIONS IN THE EVENT A CONTAINER IS FOUND TO BE LEAKING OR DAMAGED.

column168: AT APPROXIMATELY 0700 ON AUGUST 21, 1996 A TANK TRUCK OWNED BY TEXACO REFINING AND MARKETING INC. AND DRIVEN BY AN EMPLOYEE OF CONSOLIDATED PERSONNEL CORPORATION (CPC) WAS TRAVELING EAST BOUND ON INTERSTATE HWY 84 NEAR HIGHWAY MILE MARKER 289.  THE DRIVER WAS TRAVELING APPROXIMATELY 58 MPH (PER ELECTRONIC SPEED MONITOR) WHEN THE TEXACO VEHICLE LEFT THE ROAD WAY VIA THE RIGHT HAND LANE OF TRAVEL.  A ROLLOVER OF THE VEHICLE OCCURRED RESULTING IN THE LOSS OF PRODUCT (2546 GAL DIESEL). ***** PHONE CALLS TO MANAGERS WERE MADE AND AGENCIES WERE CONTACTED.  CONTRACT HELP WAS SUMMONED TO ASSIST IN REMOVAL OF THE VEHICLE AND ENVIRONMENTAL ISSUES. BOTH THE DRIVERS COMPANY AS WELL AS TEXACO CONDUCTED AN ACCIDENT INVESTIGATION.  ******* CONSOLIDATED PERSONNEL ISSUED A LIST OF MEASURES - THEY PLANNED ON TALKING WITH THEIR EMPLOYEES; A SAFETY COMMITTEE WILL REVIEW THE ACCIDENT.  A DRIVER SAFETY MEETING WILL THAN BE HELD.  THE CAUSE OF THE ACCIDENT WILL BE DISCUSSED TO PREVENT THIS PROBLEM FROM HAPPENING AGAIN.

ON 8-22-96, OUR DRIVER WAS STOPPED FOR A DOT INSPECTION.  THE OFFICER REPORTED LIQUID ON THE FLOOR AND ON THE BOTTOM RIM OF THE 55 GALLON DRUM. THE DRUM WAS PLACED IN A SALVAGE DRUM TO CORRECT THE PROBLEM.  ON 8-26-96, ENVIRONMENTAL WASTE SERVICES REMOVED THE DRUM FROM THE SALVAGE DRUM TO INSPECT THE RIM.  WE ALLOWED THE DRUM TO SIT FOR 30 MINUTES AND SAW NO VISIBLE LEAK.  WE PICKED UP THE DRUM AND CLEANED THE BOTTOM RIM AND FOUND NO VISIBLE LEAK.  THERE WAS ALSO NO FREE LIQUID IN THE SALVAGE DRUM WHEN WE REMOVED THE DRUM.  THE DRUM WAS PLACED BACK INTO THE SALVAGE DRUM AND SHIPPED TO THE DISPOSAL FACILITY.  ** ACCORDING TO DOT INSPECTOR.

column168: TOTE BIN HAD BEEN LOADED ONTO OUTBOUND UNIT AND PARKED ON THE OUTBOUND READY LINE, WHEN ABOUT ONE HOUR LATER PRODUCT WAS DISCOVERED LEAKING FROM UNDER THE TRAILER DOOR.  UNIT WAS OPENED FOR VISUAL INSPECTION AND FOUND ONE TOTE BIN WAS LEAKING.  SHIPPER WAS THEN NOTIFIED, AN MATERIAL SAFETY DATA SHEET WAS OBTAINED, AND UNIT WAS ISOLATED ON THE FACILITY YARD. ABSORBENT MATERIALS WERE THEN PLACED ON SPILLED MATERIAL, TRAILER, AND ARRANGE FOR DISPOSAL.  AFTER REMOVING TOTE BINS FROM UNIT, THE BALL VALVE HANDLE WAS FOUND TO BE ABOUT HALF OPEN.  THIS TYPE OF TOTE BIN IS REQUIRED TO HAVE A SAFETY CAP FOR THE OUTLET VALVE.  IN THIS CASE THE LEAKER WAS MISSING THIS CAP FROM THE SHIPPERS FACTORY.  HAD THE SAFETY CAP BEEN IN PLACE THIS SPILL WOULD NOT HAVE OCCURRED.
THE DRUM HAD BEEN LOADED AT A PREVIOUS ATOP. IN BETWEEN STOPS DRUM HAD TIPPED OVER AND ROLLED ONTO THE HANDLE OF THE DOLLY.  THIS CAUSED THE HANDLE TO PUNCTURE THE SIDE OF THE DRUM CAUSING THE LEAK.

SEEPAGE VERY LIGHT CONTAINER WAS REMOVED, LEAKER PLACED IN RECOVERY DRUM. ABSORBED MATERIAL USED TO ON LEAKAGE ALL AND ALSO PLACED IN RECOVERY DRUM. column168: WHEN A SMALL CAR CUT DIRECTLY IN FRONT OF OUR TRUCK, OUR DRIVER SWERVED SHARPLY TO AVOID COLLIDING WITH THE CAR.  THIS CAUSED OUR TRAILER TO OVERTURN ONTO IT'S LEFT SIDE.  THE TOP OF THE ROLLOFF CONTAINER SLID AGAINST A CONCRETE DIVIDER WALL, CAUSING THE CONTAINER'S COVER TO RIP OPEN. ALL SPILLED MATERIAL WAS CONTAINED ON THE PAVED ROADWAY.  A CLEANUP CONTRACTOR USED A FRONT-END LOADER TO PLACE ALL SPILLED MATERIAL INTO A SECOND CONTAINER.  THE ROADWAY WAS THEN WASHED DOWN BY LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT, ALL RINSATE WAS COLLECTED BY A VACUUM TRUCK, AND DISPOSED AT THE DESIGNATED DISPOSAL FACILITY.  THIS ACCIDENT WAS CAUSED BY THE INAPPROPRIATE ACTIONS OF THE PERSON DRIVING THE SMALL CAR, WHO THEN LEFT THE SCENE WITHOUT STOPPING.

AT APPROXIMATELY 0030 HOURS, AUGUST 29, 1996 CAR WAS RELEASED FOR TRANSPORTATION.

column168: 1) LIFT TRUCK DRIVER LOADING DRUMS OF HAZ WASTE ONTO TRAILER.  2)  TRAILER FLOOR HAD THREE RAISED AREAS IN STEEL PLATE IN NOSE OF TRAILER.  3) RAISED AREAS LOOKED AS THOUGH THEY WERE HIT WITH A LIFT TRUCK FORK AND BENT UP ONE INCH.  4) UPON REACHING AREA WHERE DRUMS WOULD BE SET DOWN, RAISED AREA CAUGHT ONTO THE BOTTOM OF THE DRUM, SMASHING IT BETWEEN THE RAISED AREA AND LIFT TRUCK DRUM HANDLING DEVICE (SEE ATTACHED DIAGRAMS). 5) THIS ACTION CAUSED A PUNCTURE IN THE LOWER THIRD OF THE DRUM, SPILLING APPROX 1 GAL OF LIQUID WASTE.  ANOTHER DRUM WITH SAME MATERIAL WAS DAMAGED.  6) EMPLOYEE LAID DRUM ON ITS SIDE TO PREVENT ANY FURTHER SPILLING, EXITED TRAILER, REMOVED DRUM HANDLING DEVICE, PULLED BACK INTO TRAILER, PICKED UP DRUM ON FORKS, AND REMOVED IT FROM THE TRAILER.  7) LIFT TRUCK DRIVER CONTAINED SPILL IMMEDIATELY WITH ABSORBENT MATERIAL.  8) EMERGENCY RESPONSE TEAM MEMBERS WERE NOTIFIED, ARRIVED, PATCHED LEAKING DRUM, CLEANED UP SPILL, AND PLACED PATCHED DRUM & DAMAGED DRUM (SEE #5) INTO 2 85 GALLON OVERPACK DRUMS.  9) THE TWO (2) 85 GALLON OVERPACK DRUMS WERE RELABELED AND MARKED.  10) A FOUR FOOT BY FOUR FOOT (4' X 4') WOODED SKID WAS LAID DOWN OVER THE RAISED AREA IN TRAILER.  11) THE TWO OVERPACKS WERE LOADED ONTO THE TRAILER, AND SHIPPED TO SPRING GROVE RESOURCE RECOVERY AFTER THE REST OF THE LOAD HAD BEEN PLACED ONTO THE TRAILER.  12) TO PREVENT THIS INCIDENT FROM RECURRING, AN IMPROVED INSPECTION PROCEDURE FOR HAZARDOUS MATERIALS SHIPMENTS WAS DEVELOPED, AND PREVENTATIVE INSTRUCTIONS HAVE BEEN GIVEN TO OTHER EMPLOYEES WHO PERFORM THIS TASK.

column62: Defective Component or Device; Corrosion - Exterior
column168: ON AUGUST 16, 1996 A WESTERN FARM SERVICE DRIVER PICKED UP 4,800 GALLONS OF PHOSPHORIC ACID FROM INTEL IN ALOHA, OREGON. WHEN HE RETURNED TO THE PRODUCTION PLANT AT BROOKLAKE ROAD THE PERMANENT STORAGE TANK WAS NOT READY TO RECEIVE THE PRODUCT. THE CARGO TANK WAS PARKED ON THE EAST END OF THE FACILITY. ON THE MORNING OF AUGUST 20, 1996 THE CARGO TANK WAS MOVED TO THE UNLOADING PAD AND PREPARED TO TRANSFER THE MATERIAL. IT WAS THEN THAT WESTERN FARM SERVICE EMPLOYEES NOTICED PRODUCT HAD SPILLED OUT OF THE REAR OF THE TANK. THE CAP ON THE END OF A 3/4" PIPE HAD BEEN CORRODED AND CAUSED THE PRODUCT TO SLOWLY LEAK OUT OF THE TANK. EMPLOYEE RETURNED TO THE PARKING AREA TO FIND WET SOIL, INDICATING THE SPILL AREA. THE EMPLOYEES IMMEDIATELY REPORTED THE SPILL TO THEIR SUPERVISOR AND THE PROPER REPORTING PROCESS WAS STARTED. APPROVAL FOR CLEAN UP WAS OBTAINED FROM THE OREGON DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENTAL QUALITY. THE CONTAMINATED SOIL WAS REMOVED AND THE SPREAD AGRONOMICALLY AS A FERTILIZER, WHICH IS THE PRIMARY USE FOR THE PHOSPHORIC ACID WE PURCHASE. SOIL SAMPLES WERE SENT FOR ANALYSIS TO INSURE ALL CONTAMINATED SOIL WAS REMOVED BEFORE BACKFILLING THE HOLE. TO INSURE PREVENTION OF FUTURE INCIDENTS, ALL CARGO TANKS WERE INSPECTED FOR WEAK/IMPROPER FITTINGS. THIS PROCEDURE HAS BECOME PART OF A PERIODIC INSPECTION ON ALL DOT VEHICLE.

column168: ON 8/5/96 A SPILL WAS REPORTED WITH AN ODOR AT THE HAZARDOUS MATERIAL SORT AREA.  THE LOCATION IS ABX AIR, INC., 145 HUNTER DR, WILMINGTON, OH 45177. HAZARDOUS MATERIAL COORDINATOR, ADDIE CAMPTON AND SPILL TECHNICIAN, JEFF MCLAUGHLIN RESPONDED.  UPON ARRIVAL WE DISCOVERED A FIBERBOARD BOX EMITTING AN ODOR OF FUEL AND AN OILY SPOT UPON THE BOX.  WE THEN BEGAN OUR INSPECTION OF THE SHIPMENT.  THE OUTER BOX WAS PROPERLY MARKED AND LABELED AND THE PROPER HAZARDOUS MATERIAL CERTIFICATIONS DID ACCOMPANY THE SHIPMENT.  THE INNER CONTENTS WAS FOUND TO CONTAIN ONE METAL RECEPTACLE WITH A SCREW TYPE CLOSURE.  THE CLOSURE SEEMED SECURE.  THE ONLY REASON WE COULD FIND FOR THE SHIPMENT LEAKING WAS NOT ENOUGH OUTAGE IN THE RECEPTACLE.  THIS SHIPMENT WAS PLACED IN A RECOVERY DRUM AND ALL LABELS AND MARKINGS APPLIED AND THE SHIPMENT WAS FORWARDED ON TO THE CONSIGNEE. CLEAR OF SCENE: 02:32.

I, MICHAEL A FRYE, HAZARDOUS MATERIALS COORDINATOR AND HAZARDOUS MATERIALS TECHNICIAN, RANDY WILLIAMS RESPONDED.  UPON ARRIVAL ON THE SCENE TECHNICIAN WILLIAMS DONNED AN ORGANIC VAPOR CARTRIDGE RESPIRATOR TO INVESTIGATE THE INNER CONTENTS.  INSIDE THE FIBERBOARD BOX WAS A ONE GALLON CAPACITY PLASTIC RECEPTICLE.  THE CLOSURE WAS NOT SECURED.  THIS ALLOWED SOME OF THE INNER CONTENTS TO LEAK.  THIS SHIPMENT WAS PROPERLY MARKED, LABELED AND PROPER CERTIFICATION ACCOMPANIED.  THIS SHIPMENT WAS PLACED INTO A SALVAGE DRUM AND FORWARDED ONTO ITS DESTINATION.

column168: DURING THE MORNING SORT THE BOX CAME DOWN THE SORT BELT.  THE BOX WAS FOUND TO BE RIPPED.  WHEN THE BOX WAS OPENED TO BE REPACKED, WE FOUND THE BOXES OF UNDECLARED BULLETS.  THERE WERE NO MARKINGS, LABELING, SHIPPING PAPERS OR OTHER INDICATOR TO LEAD US TO BELIEVE THE CONTENTS WERE REGULATED.  THE FREIGHT WAS REMOVED FROM THE SORT AND I NOTIFIED CAROL POLSON WITH FAA SECURITY IN LAS VEGAS.  I ADVISED THAT WE WOULD HOLD THE FREIGHT FOR HER INSPECTION.  IN ADDITION I WOULD NOTIFY THE SHIPPER AND RECIPIENT.  SHORTLY AFTERWARD I WAS NOTIFIED AGAIN BY THE RENO FEDEX STATION THAT THEY CAME ACROSS A SECOND PACKAGE FROM THE SAME SHIPPER GOING TO THE SAME RECIPIENT.  THAT BOX WAS OPENED TO REVEAL APPROXIMATELY 1000 12 GAUGE SHOTGUN SHELLS.  THAT BOX WAS ALSO WITHOUT ANY INDICATOR THAT WOULD LEAD US TO BELIEVE THE CONTENTS WERE REGULATED.  THE FAA WAS ONCE AGAIN NOTIFIED.  SINCE THEN, THE FAA HAS ADVISED THAT THEY WOULD LIKE FEDEX TO TAKE PICTURES OF THE SIX SIDED BOX AND MAKE A COPY OF THE POWERSHIP LABEL.  THAT WILL BE DONE THIS AFTERNOON.  ONCE THE EVIDENCE IS COLLECTED THE RECIPIENT WILL BE NOTIFIED THAT THEY CAN PICK UP THE SHIPMENT FROM FEDEX IN A NON-COMMERCIAL VEHICLE.  THE AIRBILL # ON PIECE #2 IS 032-1898-286. I SPOKE WITH SPEC AGENT HENDERSON WHO AUTHORIZED THE FREIGHT'S RELEASE UPON CULMINATION OF THE PICTURE TAKING.

PACKAGE WAS FOUND LEAKING ON THE ROLLERS ON THE ORANGE BELT ON DOOR #40. FIRST RESPONDER WAS NOTIFIED AND USED ALL PPE WITH THE DECISION TREE AND RESPONSE SHEETS.  ALL SALVAGEABLE MATERIAL WAS SENT BACK TO THE SHIPPER. ALL CONTAMINATED MATERIAL WAS PUT THROUGH THE DMP.  JORDAN WHO DISCOVERED THE SPILL TOUCHED THE PACKAGE AND WASHED HIS HANDS RIGHT AFTER HE REALIZED IT WAS LEAKING.

RESPONDED TO OUTBOUND 3, BAY 567.  USED DECISION TREE AND RESPONSE SHEETS FOR A FLAMMABLE LIQUID.  I THEN PROCESSED THE DAMAGED PORTION THROUGH THE DMP PROGRAM AND RETURNED THE BALANCE TO THE SHIPPER.

DOCKMAN WAS IN PROCESS OF STRIPING TRAILER.  HE ENTERED TRAILER TO PICK UP A PALLET WITH THE FORKLIFT.  THE DRUM THAT WAS PUNCTURED WAS NEXT TO THIS PALLET.  THE MAN WAS TOO FAR TO THE RIGHT OF THE PALLET AND APPLIED THE BRAKES TO AVOID THE DRUM.  HE WAS ONLY GOING CRAWL SPEED BUT THE BRAKES DID NOT CATCH AND HE JUST BARELY HIT DRUM WITH FORKLIFT BLADES, THIS PUNCTURING THE DRUM.  HE ATTEMPTED TO SEE IF HE COULD TURN THE DRUM ON ITS SIDE, BUT THE FUMES WERE VERY STRONG AND HE DID NOT WANT TO INJURE HIMSELF.  HE THEN GOT ON THE FORKLIFT AND GOT OFF THE TRAILER.  HE THEN WENT AND REPORTED THE INCIDENT TO THE SUPERVISOR.  AT THIS POINT SMOKE WAS COMING FROM THE TRAILER FROM THE PRODUCT, HITTING THE AIR.  DECISION WAS MADE TO DYKE THE REAT OF THE TRAILER WITH SPEEDI DRY AND PULL TRAILER FROM DOCK AND PUT IN YARD.  THIS WAS DONE AND THE EMERGENCY RESPONSE TEAM WAS CALLED AND THEY ARRIVED IN APPROXIMATELY (1) HOUR AND NEUTRALIZED THE PUNCTURED DRUM.  ACTION TAKEN FOR FUTURE HANDLING IS TO TAIL LOAD ALL HM DRUMS & TO HAVE PROTECTIVE DUNNAGE AROUND THE PRODUCT.  DEC WAS CALLED, SPILL REPORT #96-06262.

ON 00696 AT APPROXIMATELY 0246 HOURS, I KAREN NICHOLS/HAZARDOUS MATERIALS COORDINATOR OF ABX AIR, INC., 145 HUNTER DR, WILMINGTON, OH 45177, INVESTIGATED A LEAKING SHIPMENT IN OUR SORT FACILITY OF THE SAME ADDRESS. THE SHIPMENT WAS A FIBREBOARD BOX WITH NO HAZARDOUS MARKINGS OR LABELS, NOR DID A SHIPPERS CERTIFICATION FOR DANGEROUS GOODS ACCOMPANY THE SHPT. THERE WAS A STYROFOAM COOLER INSIDE THE FIBREBOARD BOX CONTAINING 60 X 7 OZ SPRAY CANS OF WHIPPED TOPPING.  THE CANS DID HAVE PLASTIC CAPS ON THEM. MOST OF THE PLASTIC CAPS HAD COME OFF AND THE CANS WERE SPRAYING THE PRODUCT.  IT WAS ESTIMATED THAT APPROXIMATELY 200 OZ OF THE PRODUCT WAS RELEASED.  THE SHIPMENT IS BEING HELD IN OUR HAZMAT SECURITY CAGE PENDING INSPECTION AND RELEASE BY THE FAA.

column62: Improper Preparation for Transportation; Inadequate Blocking and Bracing; Too Much Weight on Package
column168: THIS SHIPMENT WAS PICKED UP AT XPN.  THE COSO HAD A NOTATION STATING THAT IT WAS DAMAGED AT XCL.  WHEN THE SHIPMENT GOT HERE, PART OF IT WAS IN A RECOVERY DRUM WITH XBO'S ADDRESS ON IT.  THE SKID HAD FALLEN OVER THE FREIGHT THAT IT WAS DECKED ON, AND FIVE OTHER PAILS WERE CRUSHED AND LEAKING.  IT WAS EVIDENT THAT THE PAILS WERE NOT BLOCKED CORRECTLY AND SHOULD NOT HAVE BEEN DECKED.  THE MANIFEST SHOWS THAT THIS FREIGHT CAME INTO XAR RESHIP AS A XEE LEADLOAD.  MY DSR, DAVE KIMBURGH, SAID THAT HE TOLD THE RESHIP SUPERVISOR THAT THE TRAILER SMELLED LIKE SOMETHING WAS LEAKING BUT THAT IT WAS BURIED IN THE HEADLOAD AND HE COULD NOT SEE IT. THE SUPERVISOR TOLD HIM NOT TO WORRY ABOUT IT AND TO FINISH LOADING THE TRAILER.  ALSO, THE DAMAGED FREIGHT WAS LOADED NEXT TO AN OXIDIZER, WHICH ACCORDING TO THE LOADING GUIDE SHOULD NOT BE DONE.

column168: DEAN C. COOPER, MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS CONTACTED BY JEFF BROWN, OPERATIONS MANAGER, IN-TERMINAL SERVICES, UNION PACIFIC INTERMODAL FACILITY, LOS ANGELES, CALIFORNIA, WHO STATED ONE OF THE CRANE OPERATORS OBSERVED A TRAILER LEAKING WHILE IT WAS BEING REMOVED FROM THE TRAIN.  AS THE TRAILER WAS PLACARDED FLAMMABLE, IT WAS MOVED TO LOT 16 WHERE IT COULD BE ISOLATED PENDING INSPECTION.  TRAILER XTRZ 221851 ARRIVED LOS ANGELES ON THE CHLAX-05 AT 0700 HOURS, THURSDAY, AUGUST 8, 1996. MANAGER COOPER DROVE TO THE INTERMODAL FACILITY AND FOUND THE TRAILER ISOLATED IN LOT 16.  SEAL CF 531455 WAS REMOVED TO OPEN THE REAR DOORS TO INSPECT THE LADING.  THE TRAILER HAD BEEN CUBED OUT WITH LADING STACKED SOLID ACROSS THE REAR DOORWAY, WHICH DID NOT ALLOW ACCESS TO THE INTERIOR TO INVESTIGATE THE LEAKING CONTENTS.  THE PRODUCT LEAKING THROUGH THE FLOORING AT THE FRONT LANDING GEAR WAS FIELD TESTED FOR FLAMMABILITY AND FOUND TO BURN, INDICATING IT WAS THE LISTED HAZARDOUS MATERIALS THAT WERE LEAKING. ********* CONTACT WAS MADE WITH MR. JOHN DUNMIRE, MANAGER, CONSOLIDATED FREIGHT INTERMODAL OPERATIONS, LOCATED AT THE CF REGIONAL OFFICES IN MENLO PARK, CALIFORNIA, AND DEVELOPED THE LADING WAS DESTINED FOR THEIR LONG BEACH TERMINAL.  MR. DUNMIRE WAS ADVISED OF THE CONDITION OF THE LADING AND THE RECOMMENDED PROCEDURE TO LOCATE THE LEAKING CONTENTS.  AS THERE WAS NO BLOCKING OR BRACING IN THE TRAILER, AND THERE WAS EVIDENCE AT THE REAR DOORS THAT THE LADING HAD SHIFTED, MR. DUNMIRE WAS ADVISED THE RAILROAD WOULD NOT ASSUME ANY RESPONSIBILITY FOR THE DAMAGED AND LEAKING CONTENTS.  MR. DUNMIRE WAS REQUESTED TO CONTACT ENVIRONMENTAL TRANSLOADING SERVICES (ETS), THE RAILROAD'S HAZARDOUS MATERIAL CONTRACTOR, AND MAKE ARRANGEMENTS TO HAVE THE CONTENTS TRANSLOADED.  ******** ONCE THE ARRANGEMENTS WERE MADE, 2 EMPTY HIGHWAY TRAILERS, KCSZ 211645 AND REAZ 638429, WERE STAGED NEXT TO THE LEAKING TRAILER.  AS THE FREIGHT WAS DOUBLE STACKED THROUGHOUT THE TRAILER, AND THERE IS NO LOADING DOCK TO WORK FROM WITHIN THE INTERMODAL FACILITY, THE LADING WOULD HAVE TO BE REMOVED BY HAND, AS WELL AS UTILIZING PALLET JACKS, AND A FORKLIFT FOR GROUND OPERATIONS.  THE LADING COULD NOT BE DOUBLE STACKED BACK INTO THE TRANSFER TRAILERS, THEREFORE, AN ADDITONAL TRAILER HAD TO BE UTILIZED. ****** ON FRIDAY MORNING, AUGUST 9, 1996, THE TRANSFER OPERATION BEGAN BY REMOVING THE FREIGHT FROM THE REAR OF THE TRAILER. AFTER THE FIRST LEVEL OF FREIGHT WAS REMOVED, IT BECAME EVIDENT THAT THE OPERATION WAS GOING TO BE TIME CONSUMING, AS THE PALLETS CONTAINING THE FREIGHT HAD BEEN TURNED AND LOADED SIDEWAYS, NEGATING THE USE OF THE PALLET JACK.  EACH PALLET HAD TO BE BROKEN DOWN AND THE FREIGHT RELOADED ONTO AN EMPTY PALLET BEFORE IT COULD BE MOVED TO THE REAR DOORWAY FOR OFF LOADING.  THIS WENT ON THROUGH OUT THE ENTIRE LENGTH OF THE TRAILER. ****** DURING THE ENTIRE OPERATION, THE TRAILER WAS VENTILATED DUE TO THE VAPORS BEING GENERATED FROM THE LEAKING PRODUCT.  THIS ALSO CONSU

ON 081196 AT APPROX; 0530 HRS WHILE ATTEMPTING TO FIND AN AMMONIA LEAK THAT HAD BEEN REPORTED IN THE INBOUND YARD AT N. LITTLE ROCK, CTS MGR. M. KELLY INSPECTED THE ABOVE CAR. KELLY FOUND THAT THE INCH AND HALF PIPE PLUGS HAD BEEN LEFT OFF BOTH THE VAPOR AND LIQUID VALVES. CLOSER EXAMINATION OF THE VALVES BY KELLY REVEALED A SMALL AMOUNT OF VAPOR WAS BEING RELEASED FROM THE VAPOR VALVE. KELLY WAS ABLE TO TIGHTEN THE VAPOR VALVE DOWN APPROXIMATELY ONE AND ONE HALF TURNS, STOPPING THE RELEASE. KELLY REPLACED ALL THREE PIPE PLUGS AND PROPERLY SECURED THEM IN THE VALVES. KELLY CONTACTED THE SHIPPER AND ADVISED THEM TO THE PROBLEM. THE CAR WAS RELEASED TO CONTINUE ONTO ITS DESTINATION.

ON 081196 AT 0500 HRS MMM D. RANKIN CONTACTED C.T.S. MGR M. KELLY AND ADVISED THAT HE HAD BEEN CONTACTED ABOUT A STRONG ODOR OF AMMONIA COMING FROM SOMEWHERE IN THE OUTBOUND YARD. RANKIN ADVISED THAT EMPLOYEES WORKING AT THE SERVICE RAMP HAD REPORTED IT AND THAT FIVE OF THEM HAD GONE TO THE EMERGENCY ROOM TO BE CHECKED OUT. UPON ARRIVAL AT THE SCENE KELLY CONTACTED RANKIN WHO ADVISED THAT THERE WAS ONLY TWO ANHYDROUS AMMONIA CARS IN THE INBOUND YARD. KELLY INSPECTED THE ABOVE CAR AND FOUND THAT A VAPOR LEAK WAS COMING FROM THE GAUGING DEVICE. CLOSER INSPECTION REVEALED THAT THE PACKING NUT ON THE GAUGING ROD WAS NOT TIGHTENED AND WAS ALLOWING VAPOR TO BE RELEASED. column168: OUR DRIVER ARRIVED AT THE FUEL DEALER'S STATION WITH A FULL LOAD MADE UP OF FOUR PRODUCTS. HE GAUGED ALL THE TANKS AND FOUND THE DIESEL FUEL INVENTORY PLUS THE QUANTITY OF DIESEL FUEL ON THE TRUCK WOULD BE NEAR THE STORAGE TANKS SAFE FILL LEVEL. HE OBTAINED A COPY OF THE DEALER'S TANK LEVEL MONITOR READINGS WHICH CONFIRMED THE DIESEL FUEL WOULD FIT, THEN COMMENCED UNLOADING. THE TANK OVERFILL PROTECTION ACTIVATED ON THE D/F TANK STOPPING FLOW OF FUEL. HE SHUT THE TRUCK'S DRAIN VALVES, BUT THE HOSE WAS CHARGED WITH PROUCT WHICH FLOWED FROM THE TANK CONNECTION INTO THE CONTAINMENT BOX, THEN OVERFLOWED ONTO THE TRUCK PAD. IN AN ATTEMPT TO STOP THAT FLOW HE LIFTED THE NOZZLE FROM THE TANK CONNECTION, THEN HAD DIFFICULTY RESETTING IT. APPROXIMATELY 20 GALLONS OF DIESEL FUEL SPILLED OUT ONTO THE TANK PAD PAVEMENT, WHICH THE DRIVER CONTAINED AND CLEANED UP WITHOUT AFFECTING BARE SOIL OR WATERWAYS.

column168: SORT SUPERVISOR JEFF PENQUITE REPORTED A SHIPMENT EMITTING AN ODOR TO HAZMAT DISPATCH.  SHIPMENT WAS LOCATED INSIDE DOOR K-1 OF OUR SORT FACILITY.  PART TIME SPILL TECHNICIAN CAROYLN CORDREY AND PART TIME SPILL TECHNICIAN THEO GHOSTONE RESPONDED.  UPON ARRIVAL THEY FOUND A BROWN FIBERBOARD BOX SHOWING SIGNS OF LEAKAGE.  THEY OPENED THE BOX AND FOUND ONE METAL CAN WITH A SCREW TYPE CLOSURE, ONE WHITE PLASTIC CONTAINER WITH SNAP TYPE CLOSURE, AND MISCELLANOUS METAL, PAPER AND PLASTIC ITEMS.  THE METAL CAN CONTAINS ONE QUART OF JET ACRYLIC LIQUID. THE OUTSIDE OF THIS CAN HAD A WARNING LABEL THAT INCLIDES A PROPER SHIPPING NAME OF "METHYL MERTHACRAYLATE MONOMER, INHIBITED."  WARNING LABEL ALSO INDICATES THIS PRODUCT IS FLAMMABLE.  THE SHIPMEN WAS RESEALED AND HELD FOR A MATERIAL SAFETY DATA SHEET.  THE BOX WAS PLACED INSIDE A PLASTIC BAGS AND PLACED INSIDE THE SECURITY CAGE UNDER LOCK AND KEY IN THE HAZ MAT SORT AREA.  THE MATERIAL SAFETY DATA SHEET WILL BE ATTACHED TO THIS REPORT.  THERE WERE NO MARKINGS, LABELS, NO ATTACHMENTS ON THE OUTSIDE OF THIS BOX TO INDICATES THE CONTENTS ARE A REGULATED MATERIAL.

SORTER RON WALLAVCE REPORTED A LEAKING SHIPMENT IN SECONDARY 4 OF OUR SORT FACILITY. ONE EMPLOYEE IN CONTACT.  HAZMAT COORDINATOR FRAN VANCE AND PART TIME SPILL TECHNICIAN RANDY WILLIAMS RESPONDED TO THE SPILL. UPON ARRIVAL WE FOUND A BROWN FIBERBOARD BOX LEAKING A CLEAR LIQUID.  PH READING WAS 0. WE PENED THE BOX AND FOUND THE FOLLOWING:30 GLASS BOTTLES @ 13.5 ML EACH OF TRACE METALS MOX.  EACH BOTTLE WRAPPED IN PLASTIC BUBBLE WRAP.  NONE OF THESE BOTTLE LEAKED.  10 GLASS BOTTLE @ 434 ML EACH OF TRACE METALS MIX, EACH BOTTLE WRAPPED IN PLATIC BUBBLE WRAP.  ONE OF THESE BOTTLES WAS BROKEN AND LEAKED THE ENTIRE CONTENTS.  ALSO INCLUDED IN THIS SHIPMENT IS A MATERIAL SAFETY DATA SHEET FOR TRACE METALS MIX.  MSDS INDICATES THIS IS A CORROSIVE LIQUID N.O.S., THE SHIPMENT WAS RESEALED AND PLACED INSIDE A LARGE WHITE PLASTIC BAG, TAGGED AND HELD IN THE HAZ MAT SECURITY CAGE UNDER LOCK AND KEY PENDING FAA INVESTIGATION.  A COPY OF THE MSDS WILL BE ATTACHED TO THIS REPORT.  THERE WERE NO MARKINGS, LABELS OR OTHER ATTACHEMENTS ON THE OUTSIDE OF THIS BOX TO INDICATE THE CONTENTS ARE A REGULATED MATERIAL.

MR PHILLIPS STATED THAT WHEN THE BOX BE CAME DAMAGED THEY DID A TEST FOR RADIOATIVE MATERIALS AND THE SCORES WERE EXTREMELY HIGH.  THE PROPER SHIPPING NAME OF THE ITEM IS UNKNOWN DUE TO DAMAGED CONTAINER.

column168: TRIAD DRIVER KURT DAIGLE (HEREINAFTER REFERRED TO AS THE DRIVER) PICKED UP A HARD TOP ROLLOFF CONTAINER AT GEORGIA GULF CORP. (HEREINAFTER REFERRED TO AS THE GENERATOR, AROUND 11:00 A.M. THE DRIVER OBSERVED THAT NEITHER THE TAILGATE NOR THE LID OF THE CONTAINER WERE PROPERLY CLOSED. THE DRIVER OPENED THE TAILGATE REPLACED AND APPLIED SILICONE TO THE SEAL BEFORE SECURING BOTH THE LID AND TAILGATE. BOTH THE DRIVER AND A SUPERVISOR FOR THE GENERATOR WERE SATISFIED THAT THEY HAD STOPPED ANY LEAKS AND THAT THE CONTAINER WAS READY FOR SHIPMENT. THE DRIVER STATED THAT HE MADE SEVERAL ADDITIONAL STOPS TO CHECK THE CONDITION OF THE CONTAINER AND FOUND IT BE LEAK FREE UNTIL ABOUT EXIT #36 ON I-10. UPON DISCOVERY OF DRIPS OF LIQUID COMING FROM THE CONTAINER FLOOR THE DRIVER STOPPED AT THE EXIT 36 TRUCK STOP CONTAINED THE LIQUIDS BY PLACING BUCKETS UNDER THE LEAKS. THE DRIVER THEN NOTIFIED ME (CHRIS TESTA-TRIAD SAFETY DIRECTOR). I INTURN THEN CONTACTED A CLEAN UP CREW FROM ALL-WASTE ENVIRONMENTAL THIS CREW WAS UNABLE TO PERFORM THE CLEAN UP CREW OUT OF ANOTHER CLEAN UP SERVICE. I ALSO NOTIFIED THAT LOUISIANA STATE HIGHWAY PATROL AND THE LOUISIANA DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENTAL QUALITY BOTH ARRIVED AT THE SCENE. THE STATE POLICE LEFT SOON AFTER ARRIVAL. THEY MADE A DECISION TO PLUG THE LEAKS AND MOVE THE TRUCK TO LARCOS YARD AND TRANSFER THE MATERIALS TO ANOTHER CONTAINER. AFTER COMPLETION OF TRANSFER THE DRIVER CONTINUED TO HIS DESTINATION. TRIAD BELIEVES THAT THIS MATERIAL MAY HAVE CONTAINED MORE LIQUID THAN IT SHOULD HAVE. A LIKELY CAUSE FOR THIS WAS THE FACT THAT THE GENERATOR DID NOT SECURE THE BOX LID AND THERE HAD BEEN HEAVY RAINS THE DAY BEFORE THE DRIVER PICKED UP THE CONTAINER. WATER COMBINED WITH 1,2-DICHLOROETHANE COULD HAVE A NUCLEOPHILIC SUBSTITUTION REACTION CAUSING THE FREE STANDING LIQUIDS TO BE CORROSIVE. WE HAVE INCLUDED PHOTOS OF THE ROLLOFF CONTAINER TO ILLUSTRATE THE DAMAGE TO IT. NEITHER THE DRIVER NOR THE GENERATOR WOULD HAVE CONSIDERED THIS CONTAINER SHIPPABLE IN ITS PRESENT CONDITION.

REPAIRED GASKET, WHICH STOPPED LEAK.  BOB WIBLE, CHEMTREC, FILE #47304 AND TRENT KELLY, TEXAS AROMATIC, WERE NOTIFIED OF EXCEPTIONS. REGIONAL MGR R M STINE WAS NOTIFIED BY CAR FOREMAN THAT WHILE WORKING TRAIN LNH-50, CAR TMCX 23190 WAS NOTED TO HAVE SPLASHED PRODUCT FROM THE MANWAY AND A PIECE OF GASKET WAS HANGING LOOSE FROM THE NOZZLE.  INTACT SEAL "MURPHY OIL 804579" WAS REMOVED AND UPON OPENING THE COVER PLATE NOTED THE RUBBER NOZZLE GASKET WAS TORN APART, WITH A 6 INCH SECTION HANGING OUT FROM UNDER THE COVER PLATE. column168: MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, D A LOW, DURING COMPLIANCE INSPECTION OF TRAIN CYDE-30, SOUTH 11 TRACK, CHEYENNE, NOTED PRODUCT DRIPPING FROM BOTTOM OUTLET CAP.  SECURED VALVE AND TOOK 3/4 TURN ON BOTTOM OUTLET CAP, WHICH STOPPED LEAK. DOCKMAN, BARRY KORDELEWSKI, WAS LOADING A SHIPMENT INTO DOOR 163 AND DAMAGED ONE CARTON ON PRO 922-647305 BY SPEARING IT WITH A FORKLIFT BLADE. THE SPILL WAS CLEANED AND THE CARTON RETAINED AT THE TERMINAL PENDING DISPOSITION FROM SHIPPER.

WHILE UNLOADING TRAILER 19-4238, DOCKMAN, JEFF CALKINS, NOTICED SOMETHING LEAKING FROM A SKID.  WHEN PULLED OUT FROM THE TRAILER, WE FOUND TWO 5 GALLON PAILS CRUSHED FROM ANOTHER HEAVY SKID THAT WAS PLACED ON TOP CAUSING THE DAMAGE AND THE LEAK.  DAMAGED PAILS HAVE BEEN PUT IN A RECOVERY DRUM AND ARE BEING HELD ON CGI DOCK PENDING DISPOSITION.
